description.narrative: 2.3 Health workers, FCHVs and communities have increased capacity to stimulate demand for supplementation (Vitamin A, IFA, MNP) and to promote fortified foods (iodised salt, wheat flour) and a diversified diet,which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: 2. Nutrition: By 2022, children including adolescent girls and women of reproductive age have improved and equitable access to and use of adequate nutritious diet and improved nutritional care behaviour and care practices.

description.narrative: UNICEF advocacy for integrating stand-alone nutrition training modules, including micronutrient supplementation in the Comprehensive Nutrition Specific Interventions training package, (CNSI) has resulted in sustained commitment by MoHP at Federal, Provincial and Local Government Level to skills development of health workers and FCHV for improved service delivery. This contributed to maintaining high coverage vitamin A among children 6-59m. Advocacy and technical assistance informed policy decision for continuing the VAS programme and allocation of resources US$ 1.75 million for procuring nutrition commodities including Vitamin ‘A' capsule, MNP and iron folic acid tablets for 2019/2020 under red book budget of Government of Nepal. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:09/12/2019
